this can be accomplished with a single call to ``_getFiltersOrDefaults`` like this:

    return _.difference(['pending', 'running'], _getFiltersOrDefaults(RESULT_STATUS)).length === 0;

That's similar to what was being done before your patch, but it's nice to have this in a function that clearly states ``_isInProgressShown`` like you have here.

this will sometimes map a LOAD_FAILED action into a nearly identical LOAD_FAILED action, if an exception was caught inside the above switchMap where you `Observable.of(loadFailed(xhrError))`. This feels a bit brittle as someone might come in here later and not realize that "xhr" does not always mean xhr (it might be that action).

How I usually handle things like this by checking inside a `do` and throwing, basically the same way you did it above for the `!action.path` check. Then just use a single catch

```js
return contents
  .get(serverConfig, action.path, {})
  .do(xhr => {
    if (xhr.status !== 200) {
      throw new Error(xhr.response);
    }
  })
  .map(xhr => ({
    type: "LOADED",
    payload: xhr.response
  })
  .catch((xhrError: any) => Observable.of(loadFailed(xhrError)));
```

Ah, I had copy-pasted the original code so it used `${selectedDashboard}` instead of `${previous}` which was my intention.  In the intended form it wouldn't involve any other refactoring, since `div` isn't used later in the function.

Here's the current code:
```js
const div = this.$$(`.dashboard-container[data-dashboard=${previous}]`);
if (div.firstChild) {
  div.firstChild.remove();
}
```

Here's what I meant to suggest as an alternative, which adds `#dashboard` to the selector string in the same way that _selectedDashboardComponent() already does.  The benefit is that we're now targeting the dashboard child explicitly and not relying on it being the firstChild of the div.

```js
const dashboard = this.$$(`.dashboard-container[data-dashboard=${previous}] #dashboard`);
if (dashboard) {
  dashboard.remove();
}
```

